Salesforce Summer Program – Day 7
Testing, Async Apex & Salesforce DX

--------------------------------------------------

1. Why Testing Matters

Testing is very important in enterprise systems because thousands of users depend on the software every day. Small bugs can create major business problems.

Testing helps developers:
- Prevent bugs
- Ensure correct business logic
- Maintain system reliability
- Avoid data corruption
- Improve software quality

In Salesforce, testing is mandatory before deploying Apex code to production.

Without testing:
- Wrong data may be stored
- Duplicate records may occur
- Triggers may fail
- Automation may stop working
- Business processes may break

--------------------------------------------------

2. What is Asynchronous Apex?

Asynchronous Apex allows tasks to run in the background instead of immediately.

It is useful for:
- Large data processing
- Sending bulk emails
- Report generation
- External system integration
- Long-running operations

Types of Async Apex:
- Future Methods
- Queueable Apex
- Batch Apex
- Scheduled Apex

Difference:
- Synchronous = runs immediately
- Asynchronous = runs later in background

Async processing improves performance and user experience.

--------------------------------------------------

3. What is Salesforce DX?

Salesforce DX is a modern development workflow for Salesforce developers.

It provides:
- Source-driven development
- Better team collaboration
- Integration with GitHub
- CLI-based development
- Easier deployment and testing

Main tools:
- Salesforce CLI
- VS Code
- GitHub
- Scratch Orgs

Benefits:
- Faster development
- Version control
- Better teamwork
- Easier project management

--------------------------------------------------

4. Complete System Workflow

Example: College Management System

Step 1 – Student Registration
A student submits the registration form.

Step 2 – Validation Rules
Validation Rules check:
- Email format
- Required fields
- Duplicate entries
- Age validation

If validation fails, registration is stopped.

Step 3 – Flow Automation
A Flow automatically:
- Sends confirmation email
- Creates welcome notification
- Updates registration status

Step 4 – Apex Trigger
An Apex Trigger:
- Updates course seat count
- Updates student statistics
- Prevents overbooking

Step 5 – Formula Fields
Formula Fields automatically calculate:
- Remaining seats
- Attendance percentage
- Student grade status

Step 6 – Platform Events
Platform Events send notifications to connected systems when important events occur.

Example:
- New student registered
- Course full notification

Step 7 – Database Storage
Salesforce stores:
- Student records
- Course records
- Attendance data
- Registration history

Step 8 – Reports & Dashboards
Reports help administrators analyze:
- Student count
- Course popularity
- Attendance trends
- Registration statistics

--------------------------------------------------

